## How to use this template

When the `lhm-content-engine` skill drafts a Beam from a scout brief:
1. Start with the six-question structure. Not "write a Beam about X" but "answer these six questions about X in this order."
2. Draft section headers for punch, not as literal labels. Section 1 can be "The Setup" in this template doc but in the published Beam might be "Oil is up 66% in a year" or "The consumer is quietly breaking." The question answered is what matters.
3. Hit the word count targets. A Beam that blows past 900 words has lost discipline.
4. Every Beam must have the Section 5 invalidation criteria. If the analyst can't write them, the thesis isn't strong enough to publish.
5. Every Beam must name at least one pillar by number or name in Section 3.

---

## Why fixed structure

Because variable insight requires fixed frame to stand out. If every Beam has a different shape, readers spend cognitive energy orienting. If every Beam has the same shape, they spend cognitive energy on the content. That's the whole point.
